  "tldr": [
    {
      "source": "hackernews",
      "subsource": "news.ycombinator.com",
      "category": "ai",
      "title": "I built a vulnerable app and spent $1,500 seeing if LLMs could hack it",
      "url": "https://kasra.blog/blog/i-spent-1500-seeing-if-llms-could-hack-my-app/",
      "discuss_url": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48392343",
      "score": 219,
      "comments": 94,
      "author": "jc4p",
      "published": "2026-06-04T00:56:32Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Autonomous LLM agents incur high API costs ($1,500) while struggling with multi-step pentesting beyond basic, known vulnerability scanning.",
        "Models like GPT-4 require specialized tool-use scaffolding, shell execution, and precise feedback loops to exploit even simple application flaws.",
        "Current LLM reasoning limitations make autonomous hacking cost-inefficient compared to human security researchers using AI-assisted workflows."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/programming",
      "category": "engineering",
      "title": "Floating-Point Error Handling in C++: What Actually Works",
      "url": "https://johnnysswlab.com/floating-point-error-handling-in-c-what-actually-works/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/uw6wmo",
      "score": 3,
      "comments": 0,
      "author": "signal-11",
      "published": "2026-06-04T05:07:24Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Avoid compiler flags like `-ffast-math` if you rely on `std::isnan`, as they optimize away crucial NaN validation checks.",
        "Use C++ `<cfenv>` and `fetestexcept` to safely query hardware floating-point status flags instead of relying on fragile signal handlers.",
        "Perform defensive boundary checks using `std::isfinite` rather than relying on hardware traps, which cause undefined, platform-specific behavior."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/security",
      "category": "security",
      "title": "Pwnd Blaster: Hacking your PC using your speaker without ever touching it",
      "url": "https://blog.nns.ee/2026/06/03/katana-badusb/",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/mth4mj",
      "score": 42,
      "comments": 4,
      "author": "matthew2",
      "published": "2026-06-03T11:54:11Z",
      "bullets": [
        "Software can retask PC speakers into microphones, enabling remote eavesdropping and acoustic data exfiltration over air-gapped networks.",
        "Acoustic resonance attacks leverage targeted sound frequencies to disrupt hard drives, MEMS gyroscopes, and physical PC hardware integrity.",
        "Mitigate these threat vectors by disabling unused audio jacks, implementing high-pass filters, and monitoring ultrasonic frequency bands."
      ]
    },
    {
      "source": "lobsters",
      "subsource": "lobste.rs/devops",
      "category": "devops",
      "title": "github and the crime against software",
      "url": "https://eblog.fly.dev/githubbad.html",
      "discuss_url": "https://lobste.rs/s/vkoa7r",
      "score": 75,
      "comments": 32,
      "author": "abnercoimbre",
      "published": "2026-06-01T15:36:49Z",
      "bullets": [
        "GitHub centralizes Git, a natively decentralized VCS, creating single points of failure and monopolistic control over open-source distribution.",
        "Proprietary lock-in via GitHub Actions and PR APIs restricts DevOps mobility, making migration to platforms like Forgejo or GitLab difficult.",
        "Teams can mitigate centralization risks by maintaining local git mirrors and using open-source, federated CI/CD engines."
      ]
    },
